Workforce jobs by region and industry (seasonally adjusted) excel file using Standard Industrial Classification (SIC) standards

Jobs Hours

UK_Labour_Productivity_Jobs_in_Regions_by_Industry %>%
    filter(year_month == max(year_month)) %>%
    group_by(industry) %>% 
    summarise(total_jobs = sum(jobs)) %>% 
    arrange(desc(total_jobs))

`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
scotland_jobs %>%
    filter(year_month == max(year_month)) %>%
    group_by(industry) %>% 
    summarise(total_jobs = sum(jobs)) %>% 
    arrange(desc(total_jobs))

`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
UK_regional_output_per_hour %>% 
    filter(year == max(year),
           industry != "all_industries") %>%
    group_by(region, industry) %>% 
    summarise(industry_output_per_hour = sum(output_per_hour)) %>% 
    arrange(industry_output_per_hour)
`summarise()` regrouping output by 'region' (override with `.groups` argument)
UK_regional_output_per_job %>% 
    filter(year == max(year),
           industry != "all_industries") %>%
    group_by(region, industry) %>% 
    summarise(industry_output_per_job = sum(output_per_job)) %>% 
    arrange(industry_output_per_job)

`summarise()` regrouping output by 'region' (override with `.groups` argument)
UK_regional_output_per_job %>%
    filter(industry == "financial_services") %>%
    group_by(year, region, industry) %>%
    summarise(output_per_job = sum(output_per_job)) %>% 
    ggplot() +
    aes(x = year, y = output_per_job, colour = region) %>% 
    geom_line()

`summarise()` regrouping output by 'year', 'region' (override with `.groups` argument)
